</DOCID>
<HL>
   Advertising:
   Movie Theaters
   Still Running
   Ads Despite Ban
   ----
   By Joanne Lipman
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   DIS CPX TWX KO RJR EUROP SAA
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL TRADE COMMISSION (FTC)
</GV>
<LP>
   Friday night in Westhampton, Long Island. The crowd files
into the movie theater, buzzing in anticipation over "Dick
Tracy." The lights dim. All eyes turn to the screen. And then
-- commercials for Diet Coke and American Express.
   What's wrong with this picture?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Dick Tracy" is a Walt Disney release. That's the same
Disney that trumpeted its new policy, as of March, to ban
theaters from running ads before its pictures. Yet here at
the Hampton Arts theater in New York, and at dozens of other
theaters owned by Cineplex Odeon across North America,
commercials run before every showing of the Disney flick. Ads
air before Disney's "Pretty Woman," too. In all, Cineplex
Odeon is showing Disney films on 170 of its more than 1,550
screens, and isn't banning ads on any of them.
   Disney and its competitor Warner Bros., which has a
similar ad-ban policy for its films, are finding that grand
proclamations are one thing, but enforcing an ad ban in movie
theaters is something else altogether. The problem is that
theater chains such as Cineplex Odeon have long-running
contracts with advertisers, contracts that will last for
months or even years to come. "We can't force people to break
contracts," says a Disney spokeswoman, and "we've got to play
some Cineplex houses because there's so many of them."
   The upshot: the Disney and Warner ad bans may not look
like bans at all to the average man on the street.
   Cineplex isn't the only chain showing ads before Disney
and Warner pictures. Cobb Theaters, a Southern chain based in
Birmingham, Ala., with 300 screens, is doing it as well.
Cobb, too, had pre-existing agreements with advertisers. But
Cineplex, with over 1,550 screens, is the largest player
running the ads. Aside from the commercials it runs before
various Disney releases, it also allows ads before the Time
Warner films it is showing on some 230 screens, including
"Gremlins II" and "Driving Miss Daisy."
   The ads promise to be around for a long while. A
spokeswoman for Cineplex, based in Toronto, declines to say
how long the theater chain's contracts with advertisers run,
but says: "There certainly is some time to go on certain
contracts. We aren't talking about something that would
disappear almost immediately." Advertisers say such contracts
typically run several years. Cobb executives declined to
comment.
   The Disney spokeswoman says a number of other theater
owners were able to renegotiate agreements with advertisers
and to pull ads from Disney releases. For those that are
still running ads because of pre-existing contracts, the
spokeswoman says Disney hopes that the contracts won't be
renewed. "We would hope the theaters think twice about
showing advertisements at all," she says. Warner executives
couldn't be reached.
   Advertisers, though, say they have no plans to leave show
business, not as long as they can still see their ads on the
silver screen. Their contracts with such chains as Cineplex
have put them in a position where they barely have to think
about the Disney and Warner ad bans. "Right now," says a
Coca-Cola spokesman, "we have to view it for us as business
as usual."
   Although he won't speculate on what will happen after
Coke's contract with Cineplex expires, the spokesman says:
"As long as theater owners provide us an opportunity to
advertise in their chains, we will continue to evaluate that
and take advantage of it. We view theater advertising as an
effective form of advertising."
   The Cineplex spokeswoman declined to comment on how the
chain will entice such current advertisers as American
Express, Coke and the Los Angeles Times to stay on after
their contracts expire, if Disney and Warner films are no
longer part of the ad package. The movie chain is faced with
a touchy situation.
   "We have good relationships with all the studios,
including those who have said they're opposed to screen
advertising, and we intend to continue those good relations,
so we will accommodate things they feel firmly about," the
spokeswoman says. But, she adds, "Obviously, we have a
difference of opinion. Cineplex believes {screen advertising}
is appropriate and can be entertaining."
   ---
   RJR's `Mr. Fit' Ads
                                                                                                       

   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco agreed not to run ads that,
according to the Federal Trade Commission, misrepresented the
findings of a government study on smoking.
   In 1986, R.J. Reynolds, a unit of RJR Nabisco, ran a
series of print ads, one of which discussed a study funded by
the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute. The ad claimed
that the institute's so-called "Mr. Fit" study provided
scientific evidence that smoking isn't as hazardous as the
public had been led to believe.
   In a complaint filed in June 1986, the FTC claimed that
the ads misrepresented the study's findings. The FTC said
that R.J. Reynolds, among other things, failed to disclose
that the men in the study who quit smoking had a
significantly lower rate of heart disease than men who
continued to smoke.
   Under the settlement, R.J. Reynolds agreed not to
misrepresent in future ads the purpose or results of the
study. A spokeswoman for the company said that R.J. Reynolds
still believes that the ad didn't distort the report's
findings. But she added that the company agreed to the
settlement because of the length and the cost of the
litigation.
   "We decided to accept the settlement and put the matter
behind us," she said.
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   SAATCHI AGREEMENT: Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co. said it reached
an agreement with the Independent Television Association that
will allow it to continue booking air time on BBC, the
British broadcaster. ITV, a middleman between Saatchi and the
BBC, last week asked for financial guarantees because of
Saatchi's financial troubles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0121
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0121.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   White House
   Puts Forward
   Budget Proposal
   ---
   Democrats Critical of Plan
   To Reduce 1991 Deficit
   By About $50.5 Billion
   ----
   By Jeffrey H. Birnbaum and David Wessel
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
INSURANCE (INS)
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The White House put forward a new proposal
to shrink the fiscal 1991 budget deficit by about $50.5
billion, but Democrats immediately began sniping at the plan
and said it wasn't sufficient to move the budget summit
forward.
   Although House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt (D., Mo.)
emerged from the closed-door talks saying that "today
succeeded in starting serious negotiations," other Democrats
were far gloomier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman James Sasser (D., Tenn.)
called the Bush administration's proposal "a new suit on that
old corpse," while Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd
Bentsen (D., Texas) termed it "a very inadequate reply." And
House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta (D., Calif.),
among the Democrats most eager to find a deficit-reduction
compromise, said, "It's a start, but it makes for a very
difficult start."
   White House Budget Director Richard Darman, who won't
provide a written version of the proposal until today,
clearly hoped it would break the logjam that has paralyzed
the budget summit since it began in mid-May. His hopes don't
appear to have been realized. After listening to Mr. Darman's
plan yesterday, one Democrat told him, "It's so inadequate
you couldn't even respond to it," a participant at the talks
said.
   After Democratic negotiators caucused, Sen. Sasser said
there was a "general recognition that it would be almost
impossible to use as a negotiating document."
   The new $50.5 billion deficit-reduction plan builds on
proposals in President Bush's January budget that, by the
administration's new figuring, would have reduced the fiscal
1991 projected deficit by $40.5 billion, congressional
sources said. It calls for no new revenues or user fees
beyond the $20 billion outlined in the January budget.
   The plan would cut projected spending on entitlement
programs, such as the Medicare health-care program for the
elderly, by about $17 billion, compared with $14 billion in
the January budget. Mr. Darman listed a host of new
money-saving changes to entitlement programs, such as forcing
drug companies to cut prices paid by Medicaid, the
health-care program for the poor, and further trimming
federal employee health benefits.
   The administration also cut projected defense spending by
$5.9 billion, compared with a $2.3 billion cut proposed in
January. And it would cut so-called domestic discretionary
spending, programs for which Congress appropriates money
annually, by about $4 billion, compared with the $500 million
in savings outlined in January.
   "It is the beginning," Rep. Gephardt said. "We have a
long, long way to go."
   New Mexico Sen. Pete Domenici, the senior Republican on
the Senate Budget Committee, said the proposal by Mr. Darman
would reduce the deficit by $440 billion to $444 billion over
the next five years. "It is a good starting point and will
permit us to proceed with serious negotiations," he said.
Democrats predicted that the Congressional Budget Office will
estimate the savings to be much less.
   The new plan came as the congressional and White House
budget offices increased their estimates of the budget
deficit for fiscal 1991, which begins Oct. 1. Mr. Darman's
new numbers indicate that if the budget summit fails,
across-the-board spending cuts mandated by the Gramm-Rudman
deficit-reduction law could be as large as $95 billion this
fall -- even if Congress agrees to exclude spending on the
savings-and-loan bailout.
   The White House Office of Management and Budget surprised
congressional summit participants by saying it now puts the
1991 deficit at $158 billion, $20 billion more than the $138
billion estimated just a month ago and far larger than the
January forecast of $100.5 billion. The Congressional Budget
Office said the red ink will swell to $162 billion, compared
with the $131 billion it estimated in March.
   These latest numbers don't include the cost of paying for
the S&amp;L bailout. If the S&amp;L costs are counted, the OMB said
the fiscal 1991 deficit would total between $200 billion and
$222 billion, while the CBO put the deficit at $232 billion.
   "The point is the problem is getting worse," Sen. Sasser
said.
   ---
   Greg Hitt contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
