<HL>
   CBOT Options Proposals
   Win Approval From CFTC
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMODITY FUTURES TRADING COMMISSION (CFT)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Commodity Futures Trading Commission
voted to approve Chicago Board of Trade proposals to trade
options on the exchange's Tokyo stock price index-futures
contract and its long-term Japanese government bond-futures
contract.
   The option on the Tokyo stock price index, known as Topix,
will give the holder the right to buy or sell Topix futures
contracts at a specified strike price by a certain expiration
date. Option premiums will be quoted in Japanese yen.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The CFTC also directed its staff to draft an
interpretation clarifying regulatory treatment of the Brent
oil 15-day contract. The interpretation is expected to
clarify that the Brent oil contract is a forward contract and
thus exempt from CFTC jurisdiction.
   A forward contract is generally an agreement that is
privately negotiated between two commercial parties and isn't
required to be traded on a registered futures exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
