<HL>
   New Securities Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   DIS CWE MHP E FRE FNM C EUROP J.OTL FREST LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                       CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. -- $2.25 billion (redemption amount) of
liquid yield option notes, due June 27, 2005, was priced at
$411.99 per $1,000 redemption amount note for a yield to
maturity of 6%. The LYONs are zero-coupon subordinated notes
exchangeable for cash in U.S. dollars equal to the market
price of a fixed number of shares in Euro Disneyland S.C.A.'s
common stock. The debt sale is expected to result in proceeds
to Disney of $927 million. The notes are convertible into
common stock at $20.965 a share, representing a 15%
conversion premium. Rated single-A-1 by Moody's Investors
Service Inc. and single-A by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the
issue will be sold through Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   Commonwealth Edison Co. -- $260 million of 9 7/8% first
mortgage bonds, due June 15, 2020, were priced at 99.185 to
yield 9.96%. The bonds, which are non-callable for 15 years,
were priced at a spread of 1.44 percentage points above the
Treasury's 30-year bond. Rated Baa-1 by Moody's and
tripleB-plus by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through
underwriters led by Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   McGraw-Hill Inc. -- $250 million of notes, due Sept. 1,
2000, were priced at par to yield 9.43%. The non-callable
notes were priced at a spread of 0.90 percentage point above
the Treasury's 10-year note. The issue's size was increased
from $200 million. Rated single-A-1 by Moody's and
single-A-plus by Duff &amp; Phelps Inc., the issue will be sold
through underwriters led by Morgan Stanley.
   Transco Energy Co. -- $250 million two-part issue of debt
securities was priced through underwriters led by Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets. The size of the issue was increased
from $200 million. The first part, which consists of $125
million of 9 5/8% non-callable notes, due June 15, 2000, was
priced at 99.578 to yield 9.69%, a spread of 1.20 percentage
points above the Treasury's 10-year note. The second part,
which consists of $125 million of 9 7/8% non-callable
debentures, due June 15, 2020, was priced at 99 1/8 to yield
9.966%, a spread of 1.50 percentage points above the
Treasury's bellwether long bond. The issue is rated Baa-2 by
Moody's and single-A-minus by S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                        MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Commonwealth of Massachusetts -- $453 million of general
obligation bonds, consolidated loan of 1990, Series B, due
July 1, 1991-2000, 2005, 2006 and 2009, with capital
appreciation bonds due in 2001-2003, were tentatively priced
by a Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. group to yield from 6.10% in 1991
to 7.50% for capital appreciation bonds due in 2001 and 2002.
Current interest serial bonds are priced to yield from 6.10%
in 1991 to 7.10% in 1996 and 1999. Bonds due in 2000 aren't
being formally reoffered. There are $50 million of 7 1/4%
bonds in 2005 that aren't being formally reoffered. There are
$25 million of 7 1/4% bonds priced at 99.07 to yield 7.35% in
2006. There are $50 million of 7% term bonds priced at 97.25
to yield 7.27% in 2009. Capital appreciation bonds are priced
to yield to maturity from 7.20% in 2003 to 7.50% in 2001 and
2002. Bonds due in 1995, 1996, 2001, 2002 and 2005 are rated
Baa by Moody's. Bonds due in 1991-1994, 1997-1999, 2003, 2006
and 2009 are rated triple-A by Moody's because of insurance
or a letter of credit. Bonds due in 1991, 1996, 2002-2002 and
2005 are rated triple-B by S&amp;P. Bonds due in 1991-1994,
1997-1999 are rated double-A by S&amp;P because of a letter of
credit. Bonds due in 2003, 2006 and 2009 are rated triple-A
by S&amp;P because of municipal bond insurance. Bonds due in
2006, capital appreciation bonds due in 2003 and bonds due in
2009 are insured. Bonds due in 1991-1994 and 1997-1999 are
backed by a letter of credit from the New York branches of
Sumitomo Bank Ltd., Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd., Industrial
Bank of Japan Ltd. and Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. of New York.
   Commonwealth of Puerto Rico -- $250 million of bond
anticipation notes of 1990, due Sept. 26, 1990, were
tentatively priced by a Goldman Sachs group to yield 5.60% in
1990. The notes are rated MIG-1 by Moody's and SP1-Plus by
S&amp;P. The notes are backed by a letter of credit from Sumitomo
Bank Ltd.
   Development Authority of Richmond County, Ga. -- $100
million of taxable industrial development revenue bonds,
NutraSweet Project, Series 1990, due June 1, 2020, were
priced by a First Boston Corp. group to yield from 8.38% for
30-day floater bonds due in 2020 to 8.63% for one-year
optional put bonds due in 2020. There are $65 million of
one-year optional put bonds priced at par to yield 8 5/8% and
$35 million of 30-day floater bonds priced at par to yield 8
3/8%. The interest rate on the 30-day bonds is reset monthly,
and holders have a seven-day optional put, according to an
official with the underwriter. The bonds are backed by a
letter of credit from Union Bank of Switzerland and rated
triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
   Dade County Industrial Development Authority, Martin
County and St. Lucie County, Fla. -- $98.2 million of
pollution control and solid waste revenue and refunding
revenue bonds, Series 1990, Florida Power &amp; Light Co.
Project, due July 1, 2020, were tentatively priced by a
Goldman Sachs group to yield from 7.30% for non-AMT bonds due
in 2020 to 7.50% for AMT bonds due in 2020. There are $12.1
million of 7.20% Dade County pollution control revenue
refunding bonds, priced at 98.788 to yield 7.30% in 2020.
There are $76.3 million of 7.20% Martin County pollution
control revenue refunding bonds priced at 98.788 to yield
7.30% in 2020. There are $9.8 million of 7.40% St. Lucie
County solid waste disposal revenue bonds, priced at 98.812
to yield 7.50% in 2020. Interest on the St. Lucie County
bonds will be treated as a preference item in calculating the
federal alternative minimum tax that may be imposed on
certain investors. The bonds are insured and rated triple-A
by Moody's and S&amp;P.
   Philadelphia -- $75 million of gas works revenue bonds,
12th Series B, due May 15, 1991-2000, 2005 and 2020, were
tentatively priced by a First Boston group to yield from
6.00% in 1991 to 7.31% in 2020. Current interest serial bonds
are priced at par to yield from 6.00% in 1991 to 6.90% in
2000. There are $8.8 million of 7 1/8% term bonds priced at
99 1/2 to yield 7.18% in 2005. There are $55.2 million of 7
1/4% term bonds priced at 99 1/4 to yield 7.31% in 2020. The
bonds are insured and rated triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
   Yolo County Flood Control and Water Conservation District,
Calif. -- $51.1 million of certificates of participation,
Tehama Coluga Canal Water Supply Project issue, Series 1990
A, due July 15, 2005, were tentatively priced by a Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co. group to yield 7.10% in 2005. The 7%
certificates are priced at 99.079. The certificates are
insured and rated triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                        MORTGAGE
                                                                                                       

   Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp. -- $365
million of real estate mortgage investment conduit securities
is being offered in 12 classes. The issue was priced late
Tuesday. The offering, DLJ Acceptance Corp. 1990-1, is backed
by Government National Mortgage Association 10 1/2%
securities. Full details on prices, yields and spreads
weren't immediately available.
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $300.1 million of
Remic mortgage securities is being offerd by Goldman Sachs.
The offering, Series 185, is backed by Freddie Mac 9 1/2%
securities. No other information was immediately available.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
Remic mortgage securities is being offered in eight classes
by J.P. Morgan Securities. The offering, Series 1990-84, is
backed by new stripped mortgage securities formed from Fannie
Mae 9 1/2% securities. J.P. Morgan took all of the
principal-only strips from the new strips trust, FNMA SMBS
Trust 81, and most of the interest-only strips from the trust
and used them as collateral for the Remic. Full details on
prices, yields and spreads weren't immediately available.
                                                                                                       


                                                                                                       

   Chrysler Corp. -- $1.01 billion of Class A asset-backed
certificates backed by auto and light-truck loans with a
coupon rate of 9 1/4% at 99.855 to yield 9.27% through
Salomon Brothers Inc. The securities, issued through a
special purpose vehicle called U.S. Auto Receivables Trust
1990-1, were priced at a yield spread of 0.85 percentage
point over the two-year Treasury note. The underlying loans
are being serviced by Chrysler Credit Corp., a unit of
Chrysler Corp. The issue has an expected average life of 1.58
years assuming monthly payments at 1% of the original loan
balance. Underlying auto and light-truck loans have a
weighted average coupon of 11.86% and a weighted average
maturity of 3.5 years. The issue is rated triple-A by Moody's
and S&amp;P, based on the quality of the underlying loans and a
subordinated class of $100.2 million, retained by Chrysler
Financial Corp., that absorbs losses on the senior
securities. A Salomon syndicate official said the offering
was all sold.
                                                                                                       

                       EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Orix Ireland Finance PLC (Japanese parent) -- 30 billion
yen ($194.9 million) of 7% bonds due Oct. 25, 1995, priced at
101.75, via Daiwa Europe Ltd. First short coupon to float at
1/8 point above three-month London interbank offered rate.
Guaranteed by Orix Corp.
   Oil and Natural Gas Commission of India (India) -- 250
million marks ($148.9 million) of 9 1/2% bonds due July 11,
1997, priced at 100 5/8, to yield 9.37%, via Commerzbank.
Guaranteed by the state of India.
   Cassa di Risparmio delle Provincie Lombarde (Italy) -- 75
million Swiss francs ($53.1 million) of 7 1/8% privately
placed notes due July 19, 1994, priced at 101 3/4, via Banque
Paribas Suisse.
