900621-0076.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Learning from S&amp;L History
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   SLM FRE FNM
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   Perhaps the only good news coming out of the S&amp;L mess is
that it has awakened some policy makers to the $863 billion
in potential liabilities piled up by such entities as Fannie
Mae, Freddie Mac and Sallie Mae.
   Last month, a Treasury study of their financial safety and
soundness concluded that these off-budget lending
institutions must adopt stricter capital standards, a credit
rating not based on their taxpayer guarantees and full
disclosure in the federal budget. It makes little sense to
allow these entities to operate as private-sector companies
and still be backed up by federal guarantees.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   However, some of them already have started wheeling out
their lobbying guns. Three House committee chairmen -- Henry
Gonzalez and Kika de la Garza of Texas and Gus Hawkins of
California -- have written Speaker Foley demanding that
reform of these government-sponsored enterprises, or GSEs, be
taken off the table at the budget summit. That way any reform
proposals will have to be routed through their committees,
where they can be "modified."
   The sudden concern of these committee chairmen for the
prerogatives of these agencies is striking. Save for when the
Farm Credit System went bust in 1985, no one at their
respective committees could recall the last time any of them
held an oversight hearing on their financial condition. Given
the lack of attention that GSEs have received to date, the
budget summit negotiators would be remiss if they didn't put
reforming them high up on the agenda.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   NASD Plans
   A One-Share,
   One-Vote Rule
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The National Association of Securities
Dealers, in a move cheered by shareholder groups, said it
plans to introduce a "one-share, one-vote" rule similar to
that recently struck down by a federal appeals court panel.
   In an interview, NASD President Joseph Hardiman said the
group is eager to maintain the rule despite last week's
appeals court decision that the Securities and Exchange
Commission had overstepped its authority in adopting the
rule. He said he expects to present "reasonably promptly" a
proposal to the NASD advisory board and board of governors.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The move comes at a time when many on Wall Street expected
the court ruling to reignite a battle among U.S. exchanges to
lure companies to list shares. Exchanges could use relaxed
listing requirements as incentives to companies concerned
about hostile takeovers.
   But Mr. Hardiman said the NASD "is not going to trigger a
race to the bottom" in listing standards. "We will abide by
19c4 {the one-share, one-vote rule} as long as it is in
effect, and if appeals fail we hope to adopt a similar rule,"
he said.
   Mr. Hardiman said that part of the reason behind the move
is an agreement that the NASD has with states that allows the
over-the-counter market exemptions from state securities
laws. If the NASD adopts rules of corporate governance that
are more lenient than those of the exchanges, he said, NASD
dealers will fall under tougher scrutiny from state
regulators.
   Mr. Hardiman quickly added, however, that his stance "has
to be tempered by what the competition is doing." The New
York Stock Exchange adopted its own version of one-share,
one-vote after the SEC rule went into effect, but the
American Stock Exchange and Nasdaq didn't.
   Amex Chairman James Jones said the exchange is still
studying the court's decision. He added, "But the fact that
we haven't made a decision doesn't mean one thing either
way."
   A Big Board spokeswoman said: "We don't see things
changing immediately. We don't see many companies that would
want to do anything with their corporate structure that would
fall under the 19c4 rule. If they do, we would review the
rules as the situation arises."
   An SEC spokeswoman said the agency is "pleased" with the
NASD's action but declined to comment further. She said the
agency hadn't yet decided whether to appeal the court's
decision.
   The SEC's rule prohibited already traded companies from
issuing a class of common stock with lesser voting rights.
That practice had become common in the mid-1980s as a
takeover defense. But the SEC's rule was challenged by the
Business Roundtable, a trade group of large companies, which
argued that the federal rule overstepped the traditional
rights of states in corporate governance. The appeals court
agreed.
   The SEC rule never precluded public offerings from having
two classes, because shareholders buying into those offerings
would know of the limited voting rights. The agency's
argument for 19c4 was that holders shouldn't have rights
taken away when they bought the stock under other conditions.
   The NASD plan met with applause from shareholder groups.
"That was what we had pressed for: That the exchanges would
do this on their own without regulation," said Ralph
Whitworth of United Shareholders Association. "We believe
that dual-class voting is the ultimate
management-entrenchment device."
   He added that he expects the move to put pressure on the
Amex to abide by a one-share, one-vote rule, especially if
the Big Board holds the line on its 19c4-type rule.
   ---
   Craig Torres in New York contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0074
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0074.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Midlantic Expects
   To Post `Modest Loss'
   For Second Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MIDL
</CO>
<LP>
   EDISON, N.J. -- Midlantic Corp., citing "significant" new
reserves for possible loan losses, said it expects to report
"a modest loss" for the second quarter.
   The bank holding company is one of the major New Jersey
lenders to developer Donald Trump, who has been in a cash
squeeze and is holding negotiations with his lenders. But
Donald W. Ebbert Jr., senior vice president at Midlantic,
said the expected second-quarter loss isn't connected to the
Trump loans.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Despite the expected loss, Midlantic declared its
quarterly dividend of 47 cents a share on common and said it
expects "to maintain adequate coverage for non-performing
assets."
   A year earlier, net income was $61.6 million, or $1.57 a
share on a fully diluted basis. For all of 1989, net was
$206.3 million, or $5.27 a share.
   Net plunged in this year's first quarter to $1.4 million,
or one cent a share, from $59.5 million, or $1.53 a share,
fully diluted, a year earlier.
   In the first quarter, the company increased its loss
reserves with a provision of $108 million. At the time, it
cited "continuing concerns about current business conditions,
a further decline in the real estate market and an increase
in Midlantic's nonperforming loans."
   Midlantic said the office of the Comptroller of the
Currency is scheduled to examine the company next month "and
the outcome of that review will be communicated to
shareholders at the appropriate time."
   In April, Moody's Investors Service Inc. downgraded the
debt ratings of Midlantic and its units.
   In national over-the-counter trading, Midlantic closed at
$15.75, up 50 cents.
</TEXT>
