<HL>
   Westpac Joins Primary-Dealer Dropouts
   ----
   By Michael R. Sesit and Tom Herman
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   WBK
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   Another financial institution fell from the ranks of the
exclusive but brutally competitive U.S. securities dealers
that do business directly with the Federal Reserve Bank of
New York.
   Australia's Westpac Banking Corp. said it was closing its
Westpac Pollock Government Securities Inc. subsidiary
immediately. The primary dealer had losses of about $29
million in the first half of its year that began Oct. 1.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Once one of the most coveted franchises in international
finance, the group of firms that deal with the New York Fed
when it buys and sells U.S. government securities as part of
its activities to influence U.S. monetary policy -- known as
"primary dealers" -- have had a tough time making money over
the past two years.
   The U.S. government-bond business "has become very
difficult," said John R. Burrus, president and chief
executive officer of CRT Government Securities Ltd., another
primary dealer. "Trading volume is down, profit margins are
down, too, and volatility is way down from prior years."
   Westpac is Australia's biggest bank with about 118 billion
Australian dollars (US$92.5 billion) in assets, of which
roughly 10% is in the U.S. The bank said most of the closed
unit's approximately 160 employees have been dismissed.
Westpac paid $120 million for Wm. E. Pollock Government
Securities Inc., an independent securities firm, in late
1986.
   The securities subsidiary posted a deficit of $3.9 million
in fiscal 1989, ended Sept. 30, mostly because of losses
associated with a failed attempt to start up a
mortgage-backed securities operation. But Anthony J. Walton,
executive vice president and general manager at Westpac in
New York, said that the government-bond dealing operations
had remained profitable until this year.
   People in the bond market said that Westpac tried selling
the operations to France's Cie. Financiere de Paribas and a
big Japanese bank, but was unsuccessful. Paribas didn't
return a phone call for confirmation.
   Some other firms are rumored to be either on the block or
considering closing down their operations, several traders
said.
   Despite the closing, Mr. Walton said: "Westpac's other
operations in the U.S. are very healthy and very profitable."
He said the bank maintained relationships with about 250
major U.S. corporations.
   "You have to be very, very clear on focus, and we felt
that strategically the primary dealership no longer fitted as
it did in 1986," said Mr. Walton, noting the intense
competition in global securities markets. "It's a very tough
decision to give up something that so many people prize such
as this; but at the end of the day, it's the shareholder that
counts."
   Last year, two British banks -- National Westminster Bank
PLC and Lloyds Bank PLC -- abandoned the business, along with
L.F. Rothschild &amp; Co. Two dealerships were also eliminated
when Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. last year acquired the
brokerage business of Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. and
Drexel Burnham Lambert Group Inc. filed for protection under
the federal Bankruptcy Code.
   Westpac's dropout lowers to 43 the number of primary
dealers, from a peak of 46 at the end of 1988. Sixteen of the
firms are controlled by foreign institutions: eight Japanese,
three British, two Swiss and one each from Canada and Hong
Kong. The Fed also lists First Boston Corp. as a foreign
institution, because over 50% of it is owned by foreigners,
but doesn't assign it a specific national designation.
However, some people regard it as a Swiss institution,
because it is 44.5% owned by CS Holding, which also owns
Credit Suisse, a big bank.
   Still, several firms, mostly foreign, have eagerly sought
to be designated as primary dealers. A major reason is that
numerous U.S. pension funds, insurance companies and other
large institutional investors will do business only with
primary dealers. Moreover, winning admission is widely
considered a mark of prestige.
   A subsidiary of Swiss Bank Corp. became a primary dealer
in March. Last December, units of Union Bank of Switzerland
and Britain's Barclays Bank PLC joined the elite club. And
other foreign institutions, including West Germany's Deutsche
Bank AG, are waiting in the wings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0060
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0060.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Stocks Rise Slightly but Many Traders
   Await News of Treasury's Note Sale
   ----
   By Anne Newman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Over-the-counter stocks managed to close slightly higher,
but many traders awaited news of next week's sale of two-year
and four-year Treasury notes.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index rose 0.27 to 460.80, a 0.06%
gain, on 148.1 million shares, up from 143 million shares
Tuesday. Advancing stocks barely outpaced declining shares,
967 to 931.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   After opening higher, the OTC market fell prey to
profit-taking; the Nasdaq Composite Index lost 0.87 in
intraday trading before recovering. "There was some
apprehension about the Treasury's plans" for the notes sale,
said Peter Coolidge, senior OTC trader at Kidder Peabody. He
added the late-day recovery reflected optimism that the
Treasury sales wouldn't push interest rates up.
   But Mr. Coolidge said that uncertainty about economic data
due for release later this week could encourage other
investors to the sidelines. "To get a sustained rally in this
choppy market is very difficult," he said, adding that
investors remain uncertain about whether the market has
peaked.
   Two stocks gave up their gains from Tuesday. MCI
Communications eased 7/8 to 41 5/8 on more than 1.9 million
shares, pressuring the Nasdaq Utility Index down 3.72 to
655.14. Shares of the Washington, D.C., long-distance carrier
closed up 5/8 Tuesday amid expectations of a positive
announcement yesterday, traders said. The company unveiled a
new long-distance service aimed at small- to mid-sized
companies.
   Also active was Newport Pharmaceuticals, which fell 5/8 to
3 on 780,200 shares. Tuesday, the stock gained 13/16 after
reports that Scandinavian tests of its controversial drug,
isoprinosine, indicated the drug may delay the onset of AIDS
in people infected with the HIV virus. However, Food and Drug
Administration officials cautioned that the studies ran
counter to other tests of the drug and said the results must
be viewed cautiously.
   Nike leaped 2 5/8 to 77 5/8 after the Beaverton, Ore.,
athletic footwear maker declared a 2-for-1 stock split late
Tuesday. The company also said its board will ask
shareholders at the Sept. 17 annual meeting to approve a
threefold increase in the authorized shares of both the Class
A and Class B common stock. Nike also said it plans to apply
for listing of its Class B common stock on the New York Stock
Exchange after completion of the stock split.
   Marquest Medical Products jumped 1 1/2 to 9 after the
Englewood, Colo., maker of disposable medical products
reported operating profit for the fourth quarter ended March
31 of $994,000, up from $22,000 a year earlier.
   Pacific Nuclear Systems advanced 1/2 to 5 7/8 after the
Federal Way, Wash., provider of nuclear waste disposal
services said a unit of the company and a West German company
were awarded a contract to clean two steam generators for
Korea Electric Power Corp.
   Werner Enterprises added 3/4 to 18 1/2. Tuesday, the
Omaha, Neb., motor carrier declared a regular
three-cent-a-share dividend payable July 23.
   Rumors fueled a 7 3/8-point surge in the American
depositary receipts of LM Ericsson Telephone, according to
Dow Jones Professional Investor Report. Traders cited rumors
the Swedish communications equipment company will win a large
contract to supply cellular telephone equipment for the
metropolitan New York City area. However, a spokeswoman told
Professional Investor Report that the company had no
announcements, adding that she doesn't see anything
"absolutely tremendous in the foreseeable future." The ADRs
closed at a high of 224 1/8.
   Rebounding from a 1/4 drop Tuesday,
   CoreStates Financial rose 1/2 to 41 as analysts disagreed
about the effect of the Philadelphia bank's recent
acquisition of First Pennsylvania Corp., according to
Professional Investor Report. Yesterday, Merrill Lynch
analyst Livia Asher said she thinks cost savings from the
acquisition could be better than expected and could help
produce strong results in the second half.
   However, Janney Montgomery Scott analyst Richard Lawrence
on Tuesday lowered his opinion on the stock to a "sell" from
a "buy." The analyst cited concerns about the potential for
further real estate loan deterioration, especially from the
First Pennsylvania purchase, Professional Investor Report
said.
   Repligen traded more than 25 times average volume. The
Cambridge, Mass., biotechnology and health-care concern
issued two million common shares priced at $15.50 each.
Repligen fell 3/4 to 15 on 837,000 shares.
   Two financial issues tumbled as the weak Northeastern real
estate market continued to plague some banks and thrifts in
that region.
   Eastland Financial slid 5/8 to 3 after the Woonsocket,
R.I., thrift and banking holding company said that additions
to its loan-loss reserves will result in a pretax charge of
$19 million and a loss for the second quarter. The company's
management said it will recommend suspending its
10-cent-a-share dividend in the second quarter until
"appropriate levels of profitability" are restored. Eastland
Financial had net income of 22 cents a share in the second
quarter a year earlier.
   Affiliated Banc eased 1/8 to 2 1/4 after the Holyoke,
Mass., thrift said it will suspend its eight-cent-a-share
quarterly dividend indefinitely and expects to report a loss
of $3.5 million for the second quarter ending in June.
   Showbiz Pizza Time tumbled 3 1/2 to 22 1/4 after officials
of the Irving, Texas, family restaurant concern told analysts
the company expects same-store sales to be flat for the
second quarter, according to Dow Jones Professional Investor
Report. Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Richard Frank
told Professional Investor Report the company now expects to
earn about 33 cents a share, up from 21 cents a share a year
earlier, which included an eight-cent tax credit. Eppler,
Guerin &amp; Turner analyst Dennis Telzrow slashed his quarterly
earnings estimate for Showbiz Pizza Time to 32 cents a share
from 42 cents a share after the presentation, Professional
Investor Report said.
   Cross &amp; Trecker fell 1/4 to 8 3/4. Tuesday, the Bloomfield
Hills, Mich., machine-tool maker said it sold its Alliance
Automation unit in Rochester, N.Y., to closely held Ambac
International Ltd. of Dallas. Terms weren't disclosed. The
stock fell 1/4 Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0059
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0059.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   Sunny Forecast for '90s
   ----
   By Susan Lee
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   As my Midwestern granny always said: First comes the rain,
then comes the sun. First we had Ravi Batra's "Great
Depression of the 1990's" and now we have Charles R. Morris's
"The Coming Global Boom: How to Benefit Now from Tomorrow's
Dynamic World Economy" (Bantam, 267 pages, $19.95).
   Just as Mr. Batra spread darkness and gloom, so does Mr.
Morris chase away the clouds. With a chirpy optimism that
would make Doris Day cringe, Mr. Morris looks into the future
and finds it better than good, he finds it stupendous. The
1990s, he gushes, will be a decade of unparalleled economic
growth.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Unfortunately, Mr. Morris is a better critic than a seer.
He comes out on the contrarian side of many current issues,
but is maddeningly unconvincing when it comes to predicting
the future.
   Looking at the three headaches of the times -- the budget
deficit, the trade deficit and industrial policy -- Mr.
Morris finds the conventional wisdom wrong.
   To begin, the twin deficits are not really deficits. In
both cases, says Mr. Morris, the deficits are creatures of
accounting problems. The federal budget deficit failed to
deck the economy during the 1980s because it wasn't much of a
deficit in the first place; indeed, when state and local
surpluses are taken into account, government deficits were
under control. Also, because we owe the debt to ourselves,
the numbers just represent a transfer of wealth from some
citizens to others and therefore is unremarkable.
   Ditto for the trade deficit. When assets and liabilities
are properly measured, the U.S. is not the largest net debtor
nation; in fact, the U.S. may have been a creditor nation
throughout most of the 1980s. Moreover, says Mr. Morris, it's
okay for foreign investors to own assets here because it
means that foreigners have a stake in our future and, anyway,
the money they earn mostly stays here.
   As for the debate over whether the U.S. should have some
form of industrial policy to direct investment and protect
domestic industry, Mr. Morris is in the don't-be-silly camp.
He points out that industrial policies don't work -- witness
the many European failures and the big boo-boos made by
Japan's Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI).
(For example, Britain subsidized its auto companies to death
and MITI was only lukewarm on a Japanese car industry.)
   So far, so good. But then comes the embarrassing part in
which Mr. Morris describes the forces that will create a
global boom. Consider:
   First, there will be a trend toward less government
borrowing that will result in lower interest rates. (Just why
governments suddenly will stop spending more than they have,
he doesn't say.)
   All things are possible, of course, but Mr. Morris goes on
to predict that the 1990s will bring a shortage of government
bonds. The folks at Resolution Trust Corp. will be pleased to
hear that the tremendous number of bonds they must float over
the next decade to fund the thrift bailout will find an eager
market suffering under conditions of scarcity. They might
also be puzzled, quite understandably, since Mr. Morris
doesn't say how this and escalating off-budget borrowing
activities fit into his scenario.
   Second, there will be a bust in the real estate market
that will free up capital for industrial investment. This
force is a consequence of the disappearance of the causes of
the real estate boom in the 1970s. Those causes, according to
Mr. Morris, were baby boomers looking for shelter and old
folks holding on to their homes.
   Okay, but the explosion of demand for real estate also was
due to wicked inflation, which made hard assets a smart thing
to hold, and tax laws that promote investment in residential
housing. Tax laws certainly are crucial in discussing and
forecasting the real estate market, but Mr. Morris doesn't
mention them.
   Third, there will be an organizational and technological
transformation of global industries that will mean increases
in manufacturing productivity and a rise in global output.
Sure, but using a bunch of business baloney that will make
Tom Peters drool with envy, Mr. Morris does more rhapsodizing
about corporate cleverness than explaining the coming change.
   He argues that the notion of comparative advantage is
old-fashioned; in the new world of global industries,
comparative advantage will belong to companies, not
countries. Maybe, but even global industries might want to
locate in countries with good human capital, a sophisticated
infrastructure, an accommodating body of laws and, of course,
reasonable tax laws. But, again, in his rush to spread the
sunshine, Mr. Morris ignores these critical factors.
   After making these and other peculiar leaps of faith and
hopeful claims, Mr. Morris offers some disappointingly flat
investment advice. If he really believes interest rates and
inflation are coming down, then locking in a lot of long-term
Treasuries would be the way to go. But, no. Mr. Morris
classifies those as speculative and recommends, instead, that
investors diversify their portfolio of stocks and invest for
the long term. Money magazine couldn't have done better.
   It's not that Mr. Morris should have written a different
book; this one would have been just fine if he hadn't made so
many weird omissions or substituted singsong cheerfulness for
argument. It's enough to make one yearn for a thundershower.
   ---
   Ms. Lee is writing a book on the origins of economic
crisis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0058
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0058.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   RJR Nabisco's
   Junk Bonds Rise
   As Much As 6%
   ---
   Firm Says It Studies Ways
   To Retire Large Amount
   Of Troublesome Debt
   ----
   By George Anders and Peter Waldman
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   RJR
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   RJR Nabisco Inc.'s junk bonds soared as much as 6%
yesterday as the company confirmed it is considering ways to
retire "a significant amount" of its most troublesome bonds.
   As reported in yesterday's Wall Street Journal, RJR has
begun a vast refinancing effort that centers on retiring at
least $4 billion of high-yield "junk" bonds. The program is
being negotiated by RJR's main shareholder, Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co. It involves bonds that are due to have their
interest rates reset by next April; difficulties with that
reset could hurt the food and tobacco company's financial
health.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The biggest price run-up yesterday came in RJR's
convertible reset bonds of 2009, which jumped $62.50 for each
$1,200 face amount, to close at $971.25 each. Those bonds now
are regarded as likely candidates to be exchanged for cash or
a new convertible preferred stock. RJR's reset bonds of 2007,
meanwhile, climbed $42.50 for each $1,000 face amount, to
$806.25. As word of RJR's refinancing plans has gradually
emerged the past two weeks, both series of bonds have risen
nearly 15% in price.
   Junk-bond specialists were pleased about RJR's plans, but
wary of sounding too enthusiastic until it's clear that all
the necessary financing is in place. "It's pretty good news,"
said Carolyn Katz, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., "but
we have to see the precise terms first."
   RJR said it expects to finish its deliberations and start
its refinancing program by the end of July. Bankers expect
RJR to raise $2.25 billion in fresh bank loans and as much as
$1.7 billion from an equity infusion by limited partnerships
that KKR controls. In addition, RJR may issue $1.5 billion of
convertible preferred stock in exchange for some of the reset
bonds outstanding.
   If the RJR refinancing is carried out as currently
planned, it will reduce the company's debt-to-equity ratio
from a daredevil 28:1 to a more conservative, though still
high 5:1, according to sources familiar with the plan.
Although that would reduce the potential profits that the
leveraged buy-out firm of KKR can earn on the buy-out, it
would put RJR on a sounder financial footing.
   Beyond its three-paragraph news release, RJR declined to
comment on its refinancing. "We think that further
elaboration at this point would complicate things," a
spokesman said.
   Even so, some money managers quickly issued bullish
assessments of the likely refinancing package. "It's pretty
attractive," said one West Coast arbitrager, who had bought
RJR junk bonds at prices as low as 60 cents on the dollar.
"I'm not a pig," he added. "If they can get me out at 85
cents on the dollar, I'm a happy departee."
   Analysts cautioned that many junk-bond holders' selling
price appears to be 7% to 10% above whatever the current
market price is. That suggests that as the junk bonds
appreciate, RJR may have a hard time buying them back at much
less than face value.
   Some investors said the reported terms of the preferred --
a 10% dividend and conversion into RJR equity at about a 50%
premium to the indicated current market price -- seem
appealing enough. Alan Snyder, president of San
Francisco-based Snyder Capital Management, argued that the
preferred issue will compare favorably with a similar issue
of convertible preferred stock issued by Time Warner Inc.
   But a more bearish view was expressed by traders at
Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., who suggested that RJR would have to
lower the conversion premium to make the preferred trade at
face value. Terms are likely to be thrashed around for the
next month or more.
   Analysts say it's clear that KKR is choosing a more
cautious, safer course. "People believe this deal is KKR's
franchise," said Edward Mally, an analyst at Salomon Brothers
Inc. "They want to believe that at the end of the day, they
have to make it work. This isn't a situation where they can
afford to hurt bondholders."
   Executives close to RJR say an improving outlook at the
company may be encouraging KKR to invest more equity in its
buy-out. Although RJR posts net losses because of its big
interest bill, operating profit in the first quarter of this
year surged 50% from a year earlier. Its operating profit
from tobacco jumped 40% in the first quarter, robust growth
for any industry, let alone one in which domestic demand is
shrinking more than 3% a year. RJR's operating profit from
food grew 18% in the first period.
   "They're getting a hell of a lot more cash flow than they
ever expected," said a senior executive close to RJR.
   RJR also may be starting to look for growth by
acquisitions, after a flurry of divestitures the past 16
months that helped reduce debt. Since the buy-out, many
food-industry analysts have expected RJR to shed its
shredded-wheat breakfast cereal division because the unit
holds just a small slice of its market. But RJR executives
have apparently decided to hold the business for now, said an
executive close to Nabisco, and are even considering an
acquisition to increase market share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
