   ---
   TRINITY COMPUTING SYSTEMS Inc., a Houston-based maker of
computer software for hospitals, was misidentified in
Tuesday's edition in a story about capital-gains lobbying.
   (See: "Politics &amp; Policy: Backers of Capital-Gains Tax Cut
Beat Bushes to Locate Recruits for Their Lobbying Army" --
WSJ June 19, 1990)
   ---
   FLEXTRONICS Inc., an electronics manufacturer, said a
fiscal fourth-quarter loss that it expects to report stemmed
from costs associated with the sale or closure of certain
U.S. operations. In Tuesday's edition, the cause of the loss
was misstated.
