</DOCID>
<HL>
   Giving a Hand:
   Young, Urban Professionals
   Work to Show New York Cares
   ----
   By John A. Conway
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<LP>
   {From time to time in this column, The Wall Street Journal
will report on efforts by people in business to help others
in need.}
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   YUPPIE, THE 1980'S ACRONYM for "young urban professional,"
became a synonym for greedy strivers. Like most blanket
condemnations, it was wrong.
   A few typical young New York professionals banded together
in 1985 to figure out how busy people with little free time
could do volunteer work. Today, New York Cares, the
organization they formed, sends hundreds of volunteers to
staff soup kitchens, visit the elderly, haul debris at
low-cost housing sites, look after AIDS sufferers and crack
babies, tutor children, and pitch in on the myriad thankless
tasks imposed by inner-city problems.
   Real estate analyst Andrea Gittings was one of the
original four, along with Andrew Luger, now an assistant U.S.
attorney, and Jeanne Straus, who works in her family's
broadcasting business. Ms. Gittings says the idea sprang from
seeing the "people we had to step over on the way to work."
By 1988, the four had an organization, a full-time director
and a mailing address.
   The nerve center of New York Cares is a four-room walk-up
a block from Bloomingdale's, which executive director Kenneth
Adams rents for only $6,000 a year. ("The landlady like
volunteers," he says.) Besides Mr. Adams, the overhead is his
staff of three. Everything else, from paint and furniture to
computers and legal services, is donated. Working with a 1990
budget of less than $200,000, Mr. Adams runs an army of 3,000
volunteers, about 700 of them working at any one time on one
of his 60-odd "team projects." Fifty to 70 of his young
volunteers keep track of the rest, others run orientation
sessions for the approximately 130 new volunteers that show
up each month.
   The disparity between the size of Mr. Adams's army and the
number at work is dictated by the nature of New York Cares.
All are young, 25 to 35, most are single, and all have
full-time jobs. The time they give comes after (or before)
regular jobs. For some, this is once a week, for others once
a month, and some at even longer intervals.
   The wide variety of chores is an advantage. Volunteers
stand ready to give time but are not sure what jobs they can
handle. One young woman, for instance, explained that she
started taking city children on outings but discovered "I
couldn't stand kids." Now she hauls trash from housing-rehab
sites. "You'd be surprised," she says, "at the satisfaction
you can get when you see a dumpster finally fill up."
   The recruiting, all word of mouth, produces remarkably
durable connections. Founder Gittings, for example, still
puts in 15 hours a week as president and treasurer of New
York Cares and finds time to visit a disabled man each week.
Ms. Straus, a director, does the same for a house-bound
woman. Mr. Luger gave up the New York Cares presidency when
he went into public service but is still on the board and
manages one shut-in visit a week.
   Mr. Adams, a 30-year-old, Manhattan-born graduate of
Vermont's Middlebury College, passed up a shot at Yale's
management school to take on his job at New York Cares. ("My
mother still wonders.") A slender, intense embodiment of a
Central Casting yuppie, he sees New York Cares developing
into a Peace Corps for the Big Apple. He thinks it could
serve as a model for a national network of volunteer bands of
young professionals. (Two copies have been created in Atlanta
and Washington, D.C.) Now he is helping New York corporations
organize in-house volunteer organizations.
   Mr. Adams's only concern is the same one Ms. Gittings
remembers. "The volunteers are out there. Our nightmare is we
could be overwhelmed by their numbers."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   House Panel Adopts
   Measure to Let SEC
   Fine Violators of Law
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A House subcommittee approved legislation
that would expand the Securities and Exchange Commission's
power to impose fines on individuals and firms that violate
securities laws.
   The telecommunications and finance panel also passed a
bill aimed at curbing penny-stock fraud, after substantially
changing provisions opposed by the SEC and the securities
industry. Both bills now move to the full Energy and Commerce
Committee.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The civil-penalties bill, identical in most respects to
legislation recently passed by the Senate Banking Committee,
would give the SEC power to impose monetary penalties for
offenses other than insider trading, for which the agency
currently has fining power. The House bill also gives the SEC
the power to issue cease-and-desist orders to enforce the
securities laws. But compared with the Senate bill, the House
bill includes additional protections for parties subject to
such orders to assure the target's right to due process.
   In the penny-stock bill, the House subcommittee softened a
provision that would have required the creation of an
electronic system to disseminate penny-stock quotes. The
revised bill directs the SEC to adopt rules to improve
dissemination of penny-stock quotes. The revised bill also
directs the SEC to adopt rules providing for increased
disclosure of information about companies that sell penny
stocks to the public.
   Moreover, a provision in the bill that would have banned
so-called blind pools and blank-check offerings was softened
to require the SEC only to increase disclosure requirements
for such offerings. In both types of offerings, the issuers
don't have a business plan or specific assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   N.V. Philips Unveils First Phase of Plan
   To Scale Back Its Computer Operations
   ----
   By Bob Hagerty
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   PHG
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   N.V. Philips announced the first stage of a plan to
retrench its computer operations and said it hopes to end
losses in the division by the end of 1991.
   Retreating from its efforts to be a technology leader in
minicomputers, the Dutch electronics company said it plans to
eliminate 210 jobs at its data systems product group in
Apeldoorn, the Netherlands. The product group, which makes
minicomputers and related products and employs 2,100 people
world-wide, will "drastically" reduce efforts to develop
systems using its own hardware technology, Philips said.
Instead, the unit is to focus on putting together computer
systems based on industry standards and on tailoring systems
for specific industry applications. Philips's minicomputer
business specializes in systems for banks, insurers and
government agencies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The moves announced yesterday don't affect the company's
personal computer product group, whose main plant is in
Montreal, but a spokesman said further moves to restructure
the computer division would be announced later. Philips said
the restructuring is aimed at "drastically reducing costs"
and making "strategic choices" about which products it will
offer.
   Some analysts estimate that losses at Philips's computer
division totaled 150 million guilders ($80 million) in the
first quarter of 1990. A Philips spokesman yesterday would
say only that the losses are running at an annual rate in the
"hundreds of millions of guilders." The company, whose
overall net profit totaled 1.37 billion guilders in 1989,
warned last week that its 1990 results would be "very low,"
reflecting losses in the computer and semiconductor divisions
and high restructuring costs.
   Analysts called yesterday's announcement a step in the
right direction. "It's very encouraging that they are taking
the knife {to the computer division} in this fashion," said
Laurence Heyworth, an analyst at London merchant bank Robert
Fleming &amp; Co.
   Arjen Los of County NatWest Securities Ltd. in London said
the moves are a sign that Philips is putting more emphasis on
offering customers what they want rather than trying to
impose its own technology on the market. "If you can't be a
leader, you have to look for the niches and be market-driven"
rather than technology-driven, Mr. Los said.
   But he said investors are still waiting to hear Philips's
overall strategy for the computer division. Philips's new
chairman, Jan Timmer, is expected to address that question at
a shareholders meeting in Eindhoven, the Netherlands, July 2.
Mr. Timmer, whose rapid clean-up of the consumer electronics
division in the late 1980s earned him the nickname "Hurricane
Gilbert," is taking over from Cornelis van der Klugt, who was
forced to resign last month after the company said
first-quarter results tumbled unexpectedly.
   Mr. Los speculated that Philips might try to repair its
computer division enough to make it an attractive candidate
for a sale or a merger with a stronger rival. Only last week,
Philips and Ing. C. Olivetti &amp; Co. of Italy announced that
they had ended talks on possible cooperation in the computer
business. Some industry executives said the talks failed
partly because Olivetti decided that fixing Philips's
computer division would be too costly.
   Many analysts have long argued that Philips is too small
in computers to survive on its own. Dataquest Europe, a
consulting firm, ranked Philips as the 12th largest personal
computer company in Europe last year, with a market share of
2.2%. IDC Nederland estimates the computer division's sales,
including software and peripheral equipment, at $1.7 billion
a year. The division employs about 15,500 people, out of a
company total of nearly 300,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900621-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900621-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Getty Petroleum Unit
   And Offical Indicted
   In Tax-Evasion Case
</HL>
<DATE>
06/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   GTY TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A federal grand jury indicted a
gasoline-distribution unit of Getty Petroleum Corp. and one
of the unit's executives for tax evasion and conspiracy.
   Getty Petroleum, a Jericho, N.Y., independent gasoline
marketer, said Tuesday that the office of U.S. Attorney
Andrew Maloney in Brooklyn had notified the company that it
was seeking the indictment.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The four-count indictment names as defendants Getty
Terminals Corp. and William Rea, manager of the unit's Supply
and Trading department, primarily responsible for gasoline
sales.
   Also charged were John Pabone, president and owner of J&amp;J
Petroleum Inc., a Staten Island, N.Y., gasoline distributor;
and John Quock, president and owner of Tun Yung Oil Corp. and
Westwind Petroleum Inc., both New York gasoline distributors.
   A separate indictment issued yesterday charges two
brothers, Richard and Robert Kennon, with filing false
excise-tax returns and conspiracy. The Kennons are owners
and, respectively, president and vice president of three
gasoline companies: Jenny Oil Corp., Pelham, N.Y., and Oil
City Enterprises Inc. and Mount Vernon Energy Terminals Inc.,
both in Mount Vernon, N.Y.
   The indictments are part of what the Justice Department
called a continuing "multi-agency investigation into an
estimated $1 billion annual nationwide loss" of federal
gasoline and diesel excise taxes because of fraud in gasoline
wholesaling.
   Getty Terminals said it is "outraged" about the
indictment, which charges it with evading $946,000 of taxes
in 1985. The charges are "completely baseless," the company
said, and it plans a vigorous defense for itself and Mr. Rea,
who couldn't be reached for comment.
   Messrs. Quock, Pabone and Kennon couldn't be reached.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
